Code is generated one unit at a time. A unit is a child of the program root, and
it becomes one coherent piece of Python: a function, a class, or a block of
top level setup. The nodes below a unit are its detail, not separate code.

Every line you emit must be caused by exactly one node in the unit's subtree, and
you must say which. A line you cannot attribute is a line the human never asked
for, and it does not belong in the program.

Put imports at the top of the unit. They are hoisted and deduplicated when the
units are assembled in order.

A unit that demonstrates or exercises the program puts its statements under
if __name__ == "__main__": so that assembly order never changes behavior.

Emit no comments and no docstrings. The .human tree is the commentary.
